5cb6bf45-37a9-436f-b9a9-8e8d4a6f646c.document_title:
"Formulating Track Sorting as a Sequence-to-Sequence Problem using Jet Constituent Tokenization with Physics-Inspired Binning and Vector-Quantization Variational Autoencoder (VQ-VAE): A Study on the TrackML Dataset with 14,002 Custom Tokens"

Abstract: This study investigates various methods for tokenizing jet constituents, including physics-motivated binning and vector-quantization variational autoencoders (VQ-VAE), to apply in sequence-to-sequence (seq2seq) models in addressing the track sorting problem. The analysis is based on the TrackML dataset, which simulates top quark pair production from proton-proton collisions with detector occupancy and event pileup effects. The objective is to identify particles that have space points from at least six unique layers and construct a vocabulary of detector modules as token identifiers. This study advocates for the use of seq2seq models, such as Bart, to effectively sort tracks based on their labels and distances from the collision point, despite some loss of positional and other specifics due to tokenization. The research employs custom tokens for output sequence start [SOS] and end of each track [SEP], resulting in a vocabulary size of 14,002. The data comprises tracks extracted from events with particles originating from at least six unique layers - 349k tracks in the training dataset and 35k tracks in the validation dataset. Additionally, an extra testing dataset was curated consisting of tracks with an average pT below 5 GeV, totaling 67k tracks. The natural language processing procedure initiates by converting discrete tokens into a continuous, dense vector representation using Word2Vec. The model is trained under the continuous bag of words framework to foretell a target word based on all the words within a context window.
5cb6bf45-37a9-436f-b9a9-8e8d4a6f646c.excerpt_keywords: Track sorting, Sequence-to-sequence models, Jet constituents tokenization, Physics-inspired binning, Vector-quantization variational autoencoder (VQ-VAE), Top quark pair production, Detector occupancy, Event pileup.
